zooaRchGUI User Manual

Erik OtÃ¡rola-Castillo

2017-05-11

Zooarchaeology is concerned with the analysis and inference of faunal remains recovered from archaeological sites. The zooaRch package provides a Graphical User Interface (GUI) to analytical tools for zooarchaeological data in the R package. Functions in this package allow users to:

  • input
  • handle
  • visualize
  • and analyze zooarchaeological data

Useful data are available with the package. After starting zooaRch, users will have access to these data. Most datasets are in âwide formatâ. Included is Binfordâs comprehensive forager dataset (Binford 2001) made available by Dr.Â Amber Johnson from http://ajohnson.sites.truman.edu/data-and-program/. Typing â?LRBdataâ into the R (or RStudio) console provides information about the dataset. The key to this dataset is also available and provides users with descriptions of the variable names. The Binford dataset can be used as example for most functions in zooaRch.


Part 1 Installing zooaRch

Install R and RStudio

  1. Install R by downloading the latest version from the Cromprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) https://www.r-project.org/.
  2. To make coding easier, you should also download RStudio from https://www.rstudio.com/products/RStudio/#Desktop.

Install the zooaRch package

  1. FIRST, before installing the zooaRchGUI package, please make sure you have java installed for your Windows (32 and 64 bit) and Apple machines:
    1. https://www.java.com/en/download/manual.jsp
    2. Apple Macintosh machines will also NEED to have XQuartz installed, download from https://www.xquartz.org/
    3. Download and install âJAGSâ" (necessary for Bayesian computations) for your particular operating system from the download section in http://mcmc-jags.sourceforge.net/
  2. Now that you have these installed, fire up R or RStudio.
  3. Install the latest version of zooaRchGUI from
    1. CRAN:
    install.packages("zooaRchGUI", dependencies=TRUE)
    1. or github (installing devtools()):
    install.packages("devtools")
library(devtools)
install_github("zooarchGUI/zooaRchGUI", dependencies=TRUE)
  4. You can install the following necessary packages by copying and pasting the following R code into the RStudio console,
install.packages(c("ggplot2","tcltk2", "tkrplot", "car", "readxl","xlsx","foreign",
                   "maptools","spdep","raster", "tripack", "pgirmess", "geomorph", 
                   "vegan", "splancs", "rjags", dependencies = TRUE))

  1. You can also install these packages interactively by typing the names of the packages into RStudio. Get this R-studio dropdown through tools->Install Packages. Make sure âinstalled dependenciesâ is checked

  2. Once the package is installed [DONE (zooaRchGUI)], you can load the package by sending the following commands to the R-studio console:

library(zooaRchGUI)

Start up the zooaRch GUI by typing

zooaRch_GUI()

into the RStudio console. Then, the zooaRch GUI should appear

Thatâs it! You can browse through the package, import your own data, or use the included datasets in the package (see help file):

Part 2 Using zooaRch

0. Help Menu

0.1 About

The zooaRch package provides a Graphical User Interface (GUI) to analytical tools for zooarchaeological data in the R computing environment.

0.2 zooaRch User Guide

This will open the user guide to the zooaRchGUI program.

0.3 Example Data


Spatial

Spatial Polygon

This dataset is useful for functions in the spatial menu, particularly with the Ripleyâs K function. It contains an example of a spatial polygon. It can also be loaded using data(spatPOLY).

Random Spatial Points

This dataset contains an example of completely random points. It is a dataframe that is useful for functions in the spatial menu. It can also be loaded using data(randPTS). These data are particularly useful with the Ripleyâs K function.

Clustered Spatial Points

This dataset contains an example of random points in clusters. It is a dataframe that is useful for functions in the spatial menu. It can also be loaded using data(clusterPTS).

Multivariate

Binfordâs Data

This dataset is the forager database from Binford 2001. It can be used with most functions in the program. It can be loaded using data(LRBdata).

Binfordâs Variable Key

This is a dataframe containing information on all of the variables used in the Binford 2001 dataset. It can be loaded using data(LRBkey).

Site-x-Species

This is an example dataframe. It can be used in most functions in the program. It can be loaded using data(myData).

Chi Squared

Clarkson Deer Data

This is a dataframe containing the anatomical part location at the Clarkson site (Otarola-Castillo 2010 JAS). It is useful in the Chi Squared function. It can be loaded using data(ClarksonLimbLoc).

Survivorship

Garnsey Survival

This is a dataframe containing bison survival data from Speth 1983. It is useful in the survivorship function. It can be loaded using data(speth83).

Marj Rabba Survival

This is a dataframe containing survival data from the Marj Rabba site. It is useful in the survivorship function. It can be loaded using data(marjRab).

Marj Rabba Fusion

This is a dataframe containing fusion data from the Marj Rabba site. It is useful in the survivorship function. It can be loaded using data(marjRab.fuse).

Winslow Fusion

This is a dataframe containing fusion data from the Winslow site. It is useful in the survivorship function. It can be loaded using data(winslow.fuse).


1. File Menu

1.1 Open File

.csv

This function will open a window that will search a computer directory for .csv files. These files will be saved under the file name as a dataframe.

.txt

This function will open a window that will search a computer directory for .txt files. These files will be saved under the file name as a dataframe.

Excel

This function will open a window that will search a computer directory for Excel files. These files will be saved under the file name as a dataframe.

SPSS

This function will open a window that will search a computer directory for SPSS files. These files will be saved under the file name as a dataframe.

Shapefile

This function will open a window that will search a computer directory for Shapefiles. These files will be saved under the file name as a dataframe.

1.2 Save

Save As


This function will save inputted dataframes as a file type specified by the user. A dataframe can be saved as a .csv, .txt, .xlsx, .spss, or .stata. The file name can either be the same name as the dataframe or a name given by the user. The file will be saved in either the working directory or a directory given by the user.

1.3 Exit

This function will close the zooaRch program.


2. Edit Menu

2.1 Sort

Sort by Column


This function will accept a dataframe as the input value. The user can then choose which variables to sort in the dataframe with a maximum number of three variables. The data in the variables can be sorted by increasing or decreasing order. The modified dataframe will be saved in R memory under original filename.


3. Plotting Menu

3.1 Histogram



This function will create a histogram of the inputted data. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The data used to create a histogram will be selected and saved as a variable. The Y-Axis can be chosen to represent either the frequency or the density of the data represented by the variable. The histogram will be saved in R memory as the variable âResultsâ.

3.2 Multiway Histogram


This function will create a multi-way histogram. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The data used to create the multi-way histogram will be selected and saved as the plot variable. The histogram will be changed by the factor selected from the dataframe in the by factor combobox. The Y-Axis can be chosen to represent either the frequency or the density of the data represented by the variable.

3.3 Bivariate


This function will create a bivariate plot. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The first variable in the plot will be selected in the X-variable combobox. The second variable in the plot will be selected in the Y-variable combobox. The plot will have an equal aspect ratio if the checkbox is marked.

3.4 Boxplot


This function will create a boxplot. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The data used to create the boxplot will be selected and saved as a variable. The data will be plotted if the checkbox is marked. The boxplot will be saved in R memory as the variable âResultsâ.

3.5 Multiway Boxplot


This function will create a multi-way boxplot. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The variable to be plotted will be represented by the plot variable. The factor that the boxplot will be modified by is represented by the data in the factor combobox. The data will be plotted if the âplot dataâ checkbox is marked. The notch will be plotted if the âNotchâ checkbox is marked. The width of the boxplot will be proportional to the square-roots of the number of observations in the group if the âN width checkbox is marked. The boxplot will be horizontal if the checkboxâHorizontal" is marked, otherwise the boxplot will be vertical.

5. Transformations Menu

5.1 Mathematical


This function will create a mathematical transformation of the inputted data. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The data will be modified using log, log10, sqrt, arcsin, prop, or Zscore depending on which of these options are selected. Results will be saved in R memory under the filename âResultsâ. If the âappendâ checkbox is marked the output will be added onto any existing âResultsâ files in R memory.

5.2 Zooarchaeological

LSI

This function will standardize the size of the dataframe. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The column that the dataframe will be standardized to is selected in the âSelect Standardâ combobox. The resulting data is saved as âstandardsâ in R memory.

VSI


This function will standardize the size of the dataframe. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The column that the dataframe will be standardized to is selected in the âSelect Standardâ combobox. The resulting data is saved as âstandardsâ in R memory.


6. Sampling Menu

6.1 Single Sample Rarefaction


This function will perform a rarefaction analysis of a single sample. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The variable that the analysis will be done on is chosen along with the margins in which the index is computed and the conf.levels. The results can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked. The results of the analysis are saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

6.2 Multiple Sample Rarefaction*


This function will perform a rarefaction analysis for multiple samples. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The variable that the analysis will be done on is chosen along with the margins in which the index is computed and the conf.levels. The results can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked. The results of the analysis are saved in R memory as âResultsâ.


7. Diversity Menu

7.1 Diversity

Indices


This function will create the indices of a dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The indices that can be chosen are: shannon, simpson, isimpson, margalef, menhinick. The results can be appended to the original dataset if the âappendâ checkbox is marked, or saved in R memory as âResultsâ.


8. Univariate Statistics Menu

8.1 Summary Statistics

Summary Dialog


This function will create a summary of the variable selected. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The summary can be compact, or detailed. The outputs include the variance, standard deviation, interquartile range, mean, median, skewness and percentiles of data. The results are printed in the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.



8.2 Normality Test

Shapiro-Wilkâs Test


This function will perform a Shapiro-Wilkâs test on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The variable from the dataset that the test will be performed on is chosen in the âVariableâ combobox. The results will be plotted if the âqqplotâ checkbox is marked. The results will be saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

Kolmogorov-Smironov Test


This function will perform a Kolmogorov-Smirov test on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The variable from the dataset that the test will be performed on is chosen in the âVariableâ combobox. An edcf plot will be created if the âedcf plotâ checkbox is marked. The results will be saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

8.3 Means

One Sample T-Test


This function will perform a t-test on one sample. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The variable from the dataset is chosen in the âVariableâ combobox. The Mu value is inputted by the user along with the conf.level. The Alternative can be chosen to be either two-sided, less than, or greater than. The result are printed into the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

Two Sample T-Test


This function will perform a t-test on two samples. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The two variables for the test are chosen in their respective comboboxes. The conf.level is decided with the slider. The alternative can either be two-sided, less than, or greater than. The variables can be equal and/or paired if the checkboxes âvar.equalâ and âpairedâ respectively are marked. The results are printed into the consoles and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

One-Way ANOVA


This function will perform a one-way ANOVA test on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The response variable is chosen using the âResponseâ combobox. The predictor variable is selected using the âVariable 1â combobox. The results can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked. The results of the test are saved in R memory as âResultsâ. The results and summary are also printed into the console.

Factorial ANOVA


This function will perform a factorial ANOVA test on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The response variable is chosen using the âResponseâ combobox. The first and second variables are selected using the âVariable 1â and âVariable 2â respectively. The interaction between the two variables can be either multiplication or addition depending on the input in the âinteractionâ combobox. The results will be saved in R memory as âResultsâ. The results and summary are printed to the console. The result can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked.

8.4 Proportions

Chi Squared (row-by-column tests)


This function will perform the Chi Squared row-by-column test on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The first and second variable for the test must be categorical and can be selected in the âVariable 1â and âVariable 2â comboboxes respectively. The Monte Carlo value is selected using the slider, if a permutation test is desired. A Yateâs Correction will be performed during the test if the âYateâs Correctionâ is marked. The results are saved to the R memory as âResultsâ. The results are also printed in the console. Use data(âClarksonLimbLocâ) for an example, or choose appropriate categorical vaiables from data(LRBdata).

Fisherâs Exact Test


This function will perform the Fisherâs Exact test on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The first and second variable for the test must be categorical and can be selected in the âVariable 1â and âVariable 2â comboboxes respectively. The conf.level is chosen using the conf.level slider. The alternative can either be two sided, less than, or greater than. The Monte Carlo value is selected using the Monte Carlo slider. The results of the test will be printed out in the console and plotted. The results will be saved in R memory as âResultsâ. Use data(âClarksonLimbLocâ) for an example, or choose appropriate categorical vaiables from data(LRBdata).

8.5 Variances

F-Test


This function will perform a F Variance test on the selected dataset. The Monte Carlo value is selected using the slider. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The first and second variable for the test will be selected in the âVariable 1â and âVariable 2â comboboxes respectively. The conf.level is chosen using the conf.level slider. The alternative can be either two sided, less than, or greater than. The results can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked. The results are printed in the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

Bartlettâs Test


This function will perform a Bartlettâs Variance test on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The first and second variables for the test will be selected in the âVariable 1â and âVariable 2â comboboxes respectively. The results can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked. The results are printed onto the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

Leveneâs


This function will perform a Leveneâs Variance test on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The first and second variables for the test will be selected in the âVariable 1â and âVariable 2â comboboxes respectively. The center can either be the median of the data or the mean of the data. The results can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked. The results are printed in the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

8.6 Association

Correlation


This function will perform an Association test on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The first and second variables for the test will be selected in the âVariable 1â and âVariable 2â comboboxes respectively. The conf.level will be selected using the conf.level slider. The alternative can either be tow sided, less than, or greater than. The Pearsonâs r, Kendallâs tau, Spearmanâs rho, and the Covariance can be calculated if their respective checkboxes are marked. If calculated they will be saved in R memory as âPearson_Resultsâ, âKendall_Resultsâ, âSpearman_Resultsâ, and âCovariance_Resultsâ respectively. The results can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked.

Simple Linear Regression


This function will perform a simple linear regression on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The response variable and the predictor variable are chosen using the âResponseâ and âPredictorâ comboboxes respectively. The results can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked. The results are printed in the console.

Generalized Linear Model


This function will create a generalized linear model of the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The response variable is selected using the âResponseâ combobox. The first and second variable are selected using the âVariable 1â and âVariable 2â comboboxes respectively. The interaction between the variables can either be multiplication or addition depending on the selection in the interaction chosen in the âinteractionâ combobox. The distribution is determined by the âDistributionâ combobox. The distribution can be either gaussian, binomial, poisson, or gamma. The variables can be linked either by identity, logit, log, or inverse. The results can be plotted if the âplotâ checkbox is marked. The results are printed in the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

8.7 Survivorship

Survivorship


This function is will determine the survivorship of the dataset. It will accept dataframes either already in R memory or loaded by the user. The labels can be chosen using the âLabelsâ combobox to determine the dataset that the labels come from. The dataset that the model will come from is chosen using the âModelâ combobox. The conf.level is selected using the conf.level slider. The functions that can be used are either the survivorship, Mortality, or Epophyseal Fusion functions. The number of iterations that the functions are run is determined by the âIterationsâ spinbox. The results are printed in the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

D-Matrices


This function will calculate the distance function of the selected data. It will accept dataframes already in R memory or loaded by the user. The methods that the distance can be calculated are: Canberra, Euclidean, Jaccard, and Manhattan. The variables that the distance between will calculated are selected by the user. The output will be saved as a distance matrix as âD_Matrix_Resultsâ.

9.3 MANOVA

MANOVA


This function will perform a MANOVA on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes already in R memory or loaded by the user. The response and predictor variables are chosen using the âResponseâ and âPredictorâ comboboxes respectively. The interactions between the two variables can either be additive or multiplicative. The test that will be conducted can be the Wilks, Pillai, Hotelling-Lawley, Roy. The results are printed in the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

NP-MANOVA


This function will perform a NP-MANOVA on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes already in R memory or loaded by the user. 9.4 Mantel Tests

2-way Mantel*

This function will perform a 2-way Mantel test on the selected datasets. It will accept dataframes already in R memory or loaded by the user. The selected dataframes cannot contain missing values or characters. This function requires two dataframes that will be selected using their respective comboboxes. The columns that the test will be conducted on are selected using the listboxes that correspond to each of the dataframes. Multiple columns can be selected from each listbox. The distance method for each of the datasets can be either Canberra, Euclidean, Jaccard, or Manhattan. The number of permutations for the test is selected using the âPermutationsâ slider. The results will be printed in the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

3-way Mantel


This function will perform a 3-way Mantel test on the selected datasets. It will accept dataframes already in R memory or loaded by the user. The selected dataframes cannot contain missing values or characters. This function requires three dataframes that will be selected using their respective comboboxes. The columns that the test will be conducted on are selected using the listboxes that correspond to each of the dataframes. Multiple columns can be selected from each listbox. The distance method for each of the datasets can be either Canberra, Euclidean, Jaccard, or Manhattan. The number of permutations for the test is selected using the âPermutationsâ slider. The results will be printed in the console and saved in R memory as âResultsâ.

The number of axes that the analysis will use with is chosen using the âN Axesâ listbox. The number of permutations is chosen using the âPermutationsâ slider. The results of the analysis will be plotted and printed in the console. They will be saved in R memory as âVectorfit_Resultsâ.

9.6 Clustering

Hierarchical


This function will perform various hierarchical clustering methods on the selected dataset. It will accept distance matrices from the R memory or loaded by the user. The clustering method can be either Single linkage, Complete linkage, Average linkage, Centroid linkage, Mcquitty, Median linkage, Wardâs method, or Wardâs 2. The results are plotted.

K-means
Single K-means


This function will perform K-means clustering using simplified parameters. It will accept distance matrices from the R memory or loaded by the user. The selected dataset cannot contain missing values or characters. The columns that will be used are selected using the âVariablesâ listbox. Multiple columns can be chosen from the dataset. The number of clusters can be chosen using the âNumber of Clustersâ spinbox. The results can be plotted if the âPlotâ checkbox is marked. The results saved in R memory as âSingleKmeansâ.

Multiple K-means


This function will perform K-means clustering using user-inputted parameters. It will accept distance matrices from the R memory or loaded by the user. The dataset cannot contain missing values or characters. The columns that will be used are selected using the âVariablesâ listbox. Multiple columns can be chosen from the dataset. The minimum and maximum number of clusters can be chosen by the âMin Clustersâ and âMax Clustersâ spinboxes respectively. The Max number of iterations and the number of random sets that can be chosen are selected by the âMax Iterationsâ and ânstartâ spinboxes respectively. The function will be run verbose if the âVerboseâ checkbox is marked. A Scree plot will be created if the âScree Plotâ checkbox is marked. The results will be saved in R memory as âMultiKmeansâ.


10. Spatial Statistics Menu

10.1 Point Patterns

Ripleyâs K


This function will perform a Ripleyâs K analysis on the selected dataset. It will accept dataframes already in R memory or loaded by the user. It will also accept shapefiles loaded by the user. The shape of the boundary box of the Ripleyâs K function can be loaded as a shapefile by selecting the âLoadâ option. The loaded shapefile cannot contain more than one polygon. The boundary shape can also be a custom draw figure if the âCustomâ option is selected. With the custom shape a figure will appear on the console. The user will select the vertices of the shape that they wish to create. When the shape is complete the user will click finish to create the shape. The number of bins that the Ripleyâs K function will use is selected using the âBinsâ slider. The number of permutations used is determined by the âPermutationsâ slider. The results of the function will be plotted and printed in the console.

10.2 Spatial Connections

Spatially Defined Connections


This function will find spatially defined connections in the selected dataset. It will accept spatial polygon dataframes from the R memory or loaded by the user. It will also accept shapefiles loaded by the user. The spatially defined connections can be found using the Queen, Rook, Delauney, Gabriel, or Relative methods. The voroni data can be plotted if the âVoroni dataâ checkbox is marked. The results of the function are plotted.
